\begin_layout Subsection
Ionization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parts bought from Jordan of course constitutes the actual analytic instrumen
ts and is what is known as a Orthogonal Acceleration TOF which means that
 the ions to be measured enters the acceleration region orthogonal to the
 direction of flight.
 This is especially well suited to measure on externally generated ions,
 which is actually not what we have when measuring on the microreactors,
 the output from the capillary is obviously not ionized when leaving the
 reactor.
 However, the reason for choosing this type of instrument is, that we originally
 expected to used the TOF as a characterization tool for the two cluster
 source at the department, and these instrument actually do have an ionized
 output.
 This little experimental detail means, that we had to build our own ionization
 source to be able to use the instrument at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimally all ions will enter with very low energy orthogonal to the flight
 direction, zero energy in the drift direction and perfectly centered between
 the acceleration plate and the grounded grid immediately to the right.
 Of course the ions will not have ideal position and energy, which will
 ultimately set the limit of the resolution of the instrument.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our current way of ionization is both very simple, very cheap and very much
 sub-optimal.
 Originally we only wanted to make a very primitive and cheap ionization
 source to able to test the instrument by letting in a gas directly from
 a leak valve, simply just to able to tune and optimize the instrument before
 mounting it on the cluster source.
 For this purpose we realized the classic UHV Bayard-Alpert ion gauge
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BAYARD1950"

\end_inset

 might be a simple and working solution.
 After all the gauge works by ionizing gas, however in the normal operation
 mode, no ions will leave the gauge, rather they will be neutralized when
 they hit the collector and leave the gauge as non-ionized molecules.
 However, by removing the lid of the gauge and short-circuiting it to the
 grid voltage, the ions will now drift be able to escape the gauge through
 the top where the lid is now missing.
 Using this configuration approximately half of the ionized ions are expected
 to leave the ionization gauge
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nottingham1955"

\end_inset

.
 A current of approximately 3
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

A is run through the filament resulting in an emission current somewhere
 between 1 and 10,mA, in our current configuration we are not actively stabilizi
ng the emission current, and we are typically not measuring it either.
 Fixing this is very high on the to-do list since the emission current is
 most likely not especially stable which of course is very bad for the self-cons
istency of the measurements.
 The grid is biased approximately 40
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

V negative compared to the filament to accelerate electrons emitted from
 the filament towards the grid.
 This energy is very much a compromise, since for optimal ionization we
 would like much higher energies
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
REF!
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the ionization cross section for most relevant species will peak between
 100 and 150
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

eV.
 Typically ionization gauges operate in the range of 120--150
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

V for exactly this reason
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "srs_gauges"

\end_inset

.
 However, high ion energy is exactly the opposite of what we want for an
 ion source for the TOF, where we would optimally want mono-energetic ions
 of approximately 5
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

eV.
 It is evident that the difference between optimal ionization and optimal
 performance of the TOF is very large and the fact that it can be brought
 to work at all is actually quite unintuitive.
 The entire construction is placed in a flange with a small orifice which
 is differentially pumped by a turbo pump.
 Large amounts of gas can hence be dosed locally around the ion gauge while
 still maintaining a low pressure in the source region of the TOF-MS.
 The small orifice is essential in the setup to avoid high pressure in the
 acceleration region and drift tube of the TOF-MS which would cause an increase
 in dead counts on the MCP thus decreasing the signal-to-noise ratio of
 the recorded signal.
\end_layout

