\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a vacuum physicist, Benzene is a frightening compound.
 Just the fact that it contains ns no less than 12 atoms (C
\begin_inset Formula $_{6}$
\end_inset

H
\begin_inset Formula $_{6}$
\end_inset

) is certainly enough to complicate turn a typical nice and clean mass-spectrum
 into a forest of peaks on a number of very non-typical masses, the number
 of ways for benzene to crack on a filament is large
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
