key "nist-benzene"

\end_inset

, and adding isotopic effect on top of this does not help the situation.
 The total mass of 78
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

amu is also a complication in itself.
 Even though most mass spectrometers are able to operate up to 100
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

amu, the sensitivity is typically both poor and not especially well known
 at masses much over 50
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

amu.
 The TOF will not solve all these problems, the cracking pattern is still
 complicated, but at least it any sign of problems with the mass range is
 completely eliminated.
 Also the very high resolution is a great help since it completely eliminates
 cross talk between adjacent masses which can easily become a problem in
 a QMS, especially when the number of peaks in the mass spectrum is as high
 as in the case of benzene.
 
